english:
  title: Memorial of Grievance from the Queen Dowager Wang
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant humbly submits: I have heard that since ancient times, when emperors have held dominion over all lands both near and far, the ten thousand states and their peoples have all become subjects and servants. Men serve as subjects, women as servants—though their stations differ, their nature is the same; though their positions are distant, their bonds are intimate. Thus it is said: "When common folk cannot fulfill their duties, the ruler cannot accomplish his deeds."

    Now my circumstances grow dire and urgent, leaving me only to cry out to Heaven. Yet Your Majesty is as Heaven itself, and what you see and hear comes through our people. Where Heaven is silent, Your Majesty speaks in its stead. This is why I dare to offend against the majesty of Heaven and pour forth all that dwells within my heart.

    I was born at sixteen and came to serve my late husband Wang, by whom I bore two sons. The elder and the younger each took their turn at rule, yet both died young without heirs. My youngest son took the throne last, serving me with filial devotion—all the people knew this, and Heaven itself witnessed it. When Your Majesty ascended, he recognized that the Mandate of Heaven had turned and joyfully submitted himself to you. Your Majesty surely knew of his loyalty. Alas, his life was brief, and his sudden death gave rise to doubt. False rumors reached the Imperial ear, and Your Majesty's anger was surely just. Yet his death was abrupt, which is why suspicions arose—there is no other cause. Consider the traitor who killed the envoy and attempted to raise another prince as king: hearing of my son's passing while in flight, he devised his wicked scheme and fled into foreign lands, not daring to return to this day. This proves our country had no hand in it.

    I have also heard that to restore fallen states and continue broken lineages is the great work of the sage-ruler. How much more so when the state has not fallen and the line has not been broken? My son's grandson now manages state affairs temporarily, and a memorial requesting the bestowal of a posthumous name and the succession of rank was submitted long ago. Both I and all the people, old and young alike, have day and night gazed upward in hope for Your Majesty's gracious word. Yet still it has not come.

    Your Majesty embodies Heaven and Earth. Between Heaven and Earth, all things flourish and develop, each realizing its true nature. Yet alone my small state remains untouched by the transforming influence of Your Majesty. This grieves my heart deeply—truly, it grieves me.

    Moreover, my small nation borders the sea and lies adjacent to the Japanese islands, in constant conflict with them. Thus all those in power must be generals and commanders, leaving few to remain at court. Already half our strength is drawn away to serve here. Should this continue, I fear we would grow defenseless, and should the Japanese invaders gain advantage, would this not be a calamity for our small state and a concern for the court?

    Our land is poor and yields neither gold nor silver—this the Middle Kingdom well knows. As for horses: there are two kinds. The hu-horse comes from the north, while the native horse is of our own production. Our native horses are as worthless as donkeys, impossible to improve. Even hu-horses are but one or two in a hundred—this too the Middle Kingdom knows. Recently, through depredations by Japanese raiders, even these have been nearly destroyed. Though cloth is produced within our borders, supplying tens of thousands of bolts is genuinely difficult. The displaced peoples of Liaodong are even now being recruited through official proclamations. I, from my youth, have never spoken recklessly. How then would I dare deceive Heaven?

    I was born in the year Muxu of the Dade era and am now eighty-two years old. My days of taking leave of this flourishing age draw near. In truth, I cannot bear that the beautiful virtue of my departed son—his sincere devotion to your transforming influence—should fade away unrecognized, nor that my lonely orphaned grandson should have no place in this world. Thus do I transgress against propriety and lay bare my heart, hoping that Your Majesty might be awakened but once.

    If Your Majesty would show me compassion and forgiveness, bestow a posthumous name upon my late husband, issue the decree for succession of rank, and settle the matter of annual tribute so that my small state might arrange things as best it can and present local products according to the seasons, then I shall find peace in my remaining days, and my departed son too shall have the means to repay this grace in the shadow realm.

    I am but one woman who has enjoyed the support of two sons and three grandsons in succession. Yet when sudden calamity befell us, I could not lay the matter clearly before your enlightened court. How then could I ever face my late husband beneath the earth?

    When a man possesses but ten pieces of gold, he still wishes to pass them to his descendants without loss. How much more so with a nation? How much more so with a mother's love for her calf? As I present this memorial, tears stream down my face, and I know not what I say.
  footnotes:
    - This memorial was submitted by the Queen Dowager Wang, likely mother of a deposed or deceased prince, seeking imperial recognition and restoration of her son's lineage and tributary status.
    - The reference to the 'jade-horse' (胡馬) versus 'native horse' reflects the historical difficulty Korea faced in supplying quality horses to the Ming court as tribute.
    - The mention of Japanese raiders (倭賊) indicates this was written during a period of Wokou piracy that plagued Korean coasts.
    - The date 'Dade Muxu era' (大德戊戍) helps establish this as likely from the late Yuan or early Ming period when Korea maintained tributary relations with China.
